2570 LaneBitmask JoinVals::computeWriteLanes(const MachineInstr *DefMI, bool &Redef) 0
2571 const { ----
2572 LaneBitmask L; 0
2573 for (const MachineOperand &MO : DefMI->all_defs()) { 0
2574 if (MO.getReg() != Reg) 0
2575 continue; 0
2576 L |= TRI->getSubRegIndexLaneMask( 0
2577 TRI->composeSubRegIndices(SubIdx, MO.getSubReg())); 0
2578 if (MO.readsReg()) 0
2579 Redef = true; 0
2580 } ----
2581 return L; 0
2582 } ----
2583 ----
2584 std::pair ----
2585 JoinVals::followCopyChain(const VNInfo *VNI) const { 0
2586 Register TrackReg = Reg; 0
2587 ----
2588 while (!VNI->isPHIDef()) { 0
2589 SlotIndex Def = VNI->def; 0
2590 MachineInstr *MI = Indexes->getInstructionFromIndex(Def); 0
2591 assert(MI && "No defining instruction"); 0
2592 if (!MI->isFullCopy()) 0
2593 return std::make_pair(VNI, TrackReg); 0
2594 Register SrcReg = MI->getOperand(1).getReg(); 0
2595 if (!SrcReg.isVirtual()) 0
2596 return std::make_pair(VNI, TrackReg); 0
2597 ----
2598 const LiveInterval &LI = LIS->getInterval(SrcReg); 0
2599 const VNInfo *ValueIn; ----
2600 // No subrange involved. ----
2601 if (!SubRangeJoin || !LI.hasSubRanges()) { 0
2602 LiveQueryResult LRQ = LI.Query(Def); 0
2603 ValueIn = LRQ.valueIn(); 0
2604 } else { ----
2605 // Query subranges. Ensure that all matching ones take us to the same def ----
2606 // (allowing some of them to be undef). ----
2607 ValueIn = nullptr; 0
2608 for (const LiveInterval::SubRange &S : LI.subranges()) { 0
2609 // Transform lanemask to a mask in the joined live interval. ----
2610 LaneBitmask SMask = TRI->composeSubRegIndexLaneMask(SubIdx, S.LaneMask); 0
2611 if ((SMask & LaneMask).none()) 0
2612 continue; 0
2613 LiveQueryResult LRQ = S.Query(Def); 0
2614 if (!ValueIn) { 0
2615 ValueIn = LRQ.valueIn(); 0
2616 continue; 0
2617 } ----
2618 if (LRQ.valueIn() && ValueIn != LRQ.valueIn()) 0
2619 return std::make_pair(VNI, TrackReg); 0
2620 } ----
2621 } ----
2622 if (ValueIn == nullptr) { 0
2623 // Reaching an undefined value is legitimate, for example: ----
2624 // ----
2625 // 1 undef %0.sub1 = ... ;; %0.sub0 == undef ----
2626 // 2 %1 = COPY %0 ;; %1 is defined here. ----
2627 // 3 %0 = COPY %1 ;; Now %0.sub0 has a definition, ----
2628 // ;; but it's equivalent to "undef". ----
2629 return std::make_pair(nullptr, SrcReg); 0
2630 } ----
2631 VNI = ValueIn; 0
2632 TrackReg = SrcReg; 0
2633 } ----
2634 return std::make_pair(VNI, TrackReg); 0
2635 } ----
2636 ----
2637 bool JoinVals::valuesIdentical(VNInfo *Value0, VNInfo *Value1, 0
2638 const JoinVals &Other) const { ----
2639 const VNInfo *Orig0; ----
2640 Register Reg0; 0
2641 std::tie(Orig0, Reg0) = followCopyChain(Value0); 0
2642 if (Orig0 == Value1 && Reg0 == Other.Reg) 0
2643 return true; 0
2644 ----
2645 const VNInfo *Orig1; ----
2646 Register Reg1; 0
2647 std::tie(Orig1, Reg1) = Other.followCopyChain(Value1); 0
2648 // If both values are undefined, and the source registers are the same ----
2649 // register, the values are identical. Filter out cases where only one ----
2650 // value is defined. ----
2651 if (Orig0 == nullptr || Orig1 == nullptr) 0
2652 return Orig0 == Orig1 && Reg0 == Reg1; 0
2653 ----
2654 // The values are equal if they are defined at the same place and use the ----
2655 // same register. Note that we cannot compare VNInfos directly as some of ----
2656 // them might be from a copy created in mergeSubRangeInto() while the other ----
2657 // is from the original LiveInterval. ----
2658 return Orig0->def == Orig1->def && Reg0 == Reg1; 0
2659 } ----
2660 ----
2661 JoinVals::ConflictResolution ----
2662 JoinVals::analyzeValue(unsigned ValNo, JoinVals &Other) { 0
2663 Val &V = Vals[ValNo]; 0
2664 assert(!V.isAnalyzed() && "Value has already been analyzed!"); 0
2665 VNInfo *VNI = LR.getValNumInfo(ValNo); 0
2666 if (VNI->isUnused()) { 0
2667 V.WriteLanes = LaneBitmask::getAll(); 0
2668 return CR_Keep; 0
2669 } ----
2670 ----
2671 // Get the instruction defining this value, compute the lanes written. ----
2672 const MachineInstr *DefMI = nullptr; 0
2673 if (VNI->isPHIDef()) { 0
2674 // Conservatively assume that all lanes in a PHI are valid. ----
2675 LaneBitmask Lanes = SubRangeJoin ? LaneBitmask::getLane(0) 0
2676 : TRI->getSubRegIndexLaneMask(SubIdx); 0
2677 V.ValidLanes = V.WriteLanes = Lanes; 0
2678 } else { ----
2679 DefMI = Indexes->getInstructionFromIndex(VNI->def); 0
2680 assert(DefMI != nullptr); 0
2681 if (SubRangeJoin) { 0
2682 // We don't care about the lanes when joining subregister ranges. ----
2683 V.WriteLanes = V.ValidLanes = LaneBitmask::getLane(0); 0
2684 if (DefMI->isImplicitDef()) { 0
2685 V.ValidLanes = LaneBitmask::getNone(); 0
2686 V.ErasableImplicitDef = true; 0
2687 } ----
2688 } else { ----
2689 bool Redef = false; 0
2690 V.ValidLanes = V.WriteLanes = computeWriteLanes(DefMI, Redef); 0
2691 ----
2692 // If this is a read-modify-write instruction, there may be more valid ----
2693 // lanes than the ones written by this instruction. ----
2694 // This only covers partial redef operands. DefMI may have normal use ----
2695 // operands reading the register. They don't contribute valid lanes. ----
2696 // ----
2697 // This adds ssub1 to the set of valid lanes in %src: ----
2698 // ----
2699 // %src:ssub1 = FOO ----
2700 // ----
2701 // This leaves only ssub1 valid, making any other lanes undef: ----
2702 // ----
2703 // %src:ssub1 = FOO %src:ssub2 ----
2704 // ----
2705 // The flag on the def operand means that old lane values are ----
2706 // not important. ----
2707 if (Redef) { 0
2708 V.RedefVNI = LR.Query(VNI->def).valueIn(); 0
2709 assert((TrackSubRegLiveness || V.RedefVNI) && 0
2710 "Instruction is reading nonexistent value"); ----
2711 if (V.RedefVNI != nullptr) { 0
2712 computeAssignment(V.RedefVNI->id, Other); 0
2713 V.ValidLanes |= Vals[V.RedefVNI->id].ValidLanes; 0
2714 } ----
2715 } ----
2716 ----
2717 // An IMPLICIT_DEF writes undef values. ----
2718 if (DefMI->isImplicitDef()) { 0
2719 // We normally expect IMPLICIT_DEF values to be live only until the end ----
2720 // of their block. If the value is really live longer and gets pruned in ----
2721 // another block, this flag is cleared again. ----
2722 // ----
2723 // Clearing the valid lanes is deferred until it is sure this can be ----
2724 // erased. ----
2725 V.ErasableImplicitDef = true; 0
2726 } ----
2727 } ----
2728 } ----
2729 ----
2730 // Find the value in Other that overlaps VNI->def, if any. ----
2731 LiveQueryResult OtherLRQ = Other.LR.Query(VNI->def); 0
2732 ----
2733 // It is possible that both values are defined by the same instruction, or ----
2734 // the values are PHIs defined in the same block. When that happens, the two ----
2735 // values should be merged into one, but not into any preceding value. ----
2736 // The first value defined or visited gets CR_Keep, the other gets CR_Merge. ----
2737 if (VNInfo *OtherVNI = OtherLRQ.valueDefined()) { 0
2738 assert(SlotIndex::isSameInstr(VNI->def, OtherVNI->def) && "Broken LRQ"); 0
2739 ----
2740 // One value stays, the other is merged. Keep the earlier one, or the first ----
2741 // one we see. ----
2742 if (OtherVNI->def < VNI->def) 0
2743 Other.computeAssignment(OtherVNI->id, *this); 0
2744 else if (VNI->def < OtherVNI->def && OtherLRQ.valueIn()) { 0
2745 // This is an early-clobber def overlapping a live-in value in the other ----
2746 // register. Not mergeable. ----
2747 V.OtherVNI = OtherLRQ.valueIn(); 0
2748 return CR_Impossible; 0
2749 } ----
2750 V.OtherVNI = OtherVNI; 0
2751 Val &OtherV = Other.Vals[OtherVNI->id]; 0
2752 // Keep this value, check for conflicts when analyzing OtherVNI. Avoid ----
2753 // revisiting OtherVNI->id in JoinVals::computeAssignment() below before it ----
2754 // is assigned. ----
2755 if (!OtherV.isAnalyzed() || Other.Assignments[OtherVNI->id] == -1) 0
2756 return CR_Keep; 0
2757 // Both sides have been analyzed now. ----
2758 // Allow overlapping PHI values. Any real interference would show up in a ----
2759 // predecessor, the PHI itself can't introduce any conflicts. ----
2760 if (VNI->isPHIDef()) 0
2761 return CR_Merge; 0
2762 if ((V.ValidLanes & OtherV.ValidLanes).any()) 0
2763 // Overlapping lanes can't be resolved. ----
2764 return CR_Impossible; 0
2765 else ----
2766 return CR_Merge; 0
2767 } ----
2768 ----
2769 // No simultaneous def. Is Other live at the def? ----
2770 V.OtherVNI = OtherLRQ.valueIn(); 0
2771 if (!V.OtherVNI) 0
2772 // No overlap, no conflict. ----
2773 return CR_Keep; 0
2774 ----
2775 assert(!SlotIndex::isSameInstr(VNI->def, V.OtherVNI->def) && "Broken LRQ"); 0
2776 ----
2777 // We have overlapping values, or possibly a kill of Other. ----
2778 // Recursively compute assignments up the dominator tree. ----
2779 Other.computeAssignment(V.OtherVNI->id, *this); 0
2780 Val &OtherV = Other.Vals[V.OtherVNI->id]; 0
2781 ----
2782 if (OtherV.ErasableImplicitDef) { 0
2783 // Check if OtherV is an IMPLICIT_DEF that extends beyond its basic block. ----
2784 // This shouldn't normally happen, but ProcessImplicitDefs can leave such ----
2785 // IMPLICIT_DEF instructions behind, and there is nothing wrong with it ----
2786 // technically. ----
2787 // ----
2788 // When it happens, treat that IMPLICIT_DEF as a normal value, and don't try ----
2789 // to erase the IMPLICIT_DEF instruction. ----
2790 MachineBasicBlock *OtherMBB = Indexes->getMBBFromIndex(V.OtherVNI->def); 0
2791 if (DefMI && DefMI->getParent() != OtherMBB) { 0
2792 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "IMPLICIT_DEF defined at " << V.OtherVNI->def 0
2793 << " extends into " ----
2794 << printMBBReference(*DefMI->getParent()) ----
2795 << ", keeping it.\n"); ----
2796 OtherV.ErasableImplicitDef = false; 0
2797 } else if (OtherMBB->hasEHPadSuccessor()) { 0
2798 // If OtherV is defined in a basic block that has EH pad successors then ----
2799 // we get the same problem not just if OtherV is live beyond its basic ----
2800 // block, but beyond the last call instruction in its basic block. Handle ----
2801 // this case conservatively. ----
2802 LLVM_DEBUG( 0
2803 dbgs() << "IMPLICIT_DEF defined at " << V.OtherVNI->def ----
2804 << " may be live into EH pad successors, keeping it.\n"); ----
2805 OtherV.ErasableImplicitDef = false; 0
2806 } else { ----
2807 // We deferred clearing these lanes in case we needed to save them ----
2808 OtherV.ValidLanes &= ~OtherV.WriteLanes; 0
2809 } ----
2810 } ----
2811 ----
2812 // Allow overlapping PHI values. Any real interference would show up in a ----
2813 // predecessor, the PHI itself can't introduce any conflicts. ----
2814 if (VNI->isPHIDef()) 0
2815 return CR_Replace; 0
2816 ----
2817 // Check for simple erasable conflicts. ----
2818 if (DefMI->isImplicitDef()) 0
2819 return CR_Erase; 0
2820 ----
2821 // Include the non-conflict where DefMI is a coalescable copy that kills ----
2822 // OtherVNI. We still want the copy erased and value numbers merged. ----
2823 if (CP.isCoalescable(DefMI)) { 0
2824 // Some of the lanes copied from OtherVNI may be undef, making them undef ----
2825 // here too. ----
2826 V.ValidLanes &= ~V.WriteLanes | OtherV.ValidLanes; 0
2827 return CR_Erase; 0
2828 } ----
2829 ----
2830 // This may not be a real conflict if DefMI simply kills Other and defines ----
2831 // VNI. ----
2832 if (OtherLRQ.isKill() && OtherLRQ.endPoint() <= VNI->def) 0
2833 return CR_Keep; 0
2834 ----
2835 // Handle the case where VNI and OtherVNI can be proven to be identical: ----
2836 // ----
2837 // %other = COPY %ext ----
2838 // %this = COPY %ext <-- Erase this copy ----
2839 // ----
2840 if (DefMI->isFullCopy() && !CP.isPartial() && 0
2841 valuesIdentical(VNI, V.OtherVNI, Other)) { 0
2842 V.Identical = true; 0
2843 return CR_Erase; 0
2844 } ----
2845 ----
2846 // The remaining checks apply to the lanes, which aren't tracked here. This ----
2847 // was already decided to be OK via the following CR_Replace condition. ----
2848 // CR_Replace. ----
2849 if (SubRangeJoin) 0
2850 return CR_Replace; 0
2851 ----
2852 // If the lanes written by this instruction were all undef in OtherVNI, it is ----
2853 // still safe to join the live ranges. This can't be done with a simple value ----
2854 // mapping, though - OtherVNI will map to multiple values: ----
2855 // ----
2856 // 1 %dst:ssub0 = FOO <-- OtherVNI ----
2857 // 2 %src = BAR <-- VNI ----
2858 // 3 %dst:ssub1 = COPY killed %src <-- Eliminate this copy. ----
2859 // 4 BAZ killed %dst ----
2860 // 5 QUUX killed %src ----
2861 // ----
2862 // Here OtherVNI will map to itself in [1;2), but to VNI in [2;5). CR_Replace ----
2863 // handles this complex value mapping. ----
2864 if ((V.WriteLanes & OtherV.ValidLanes).none()) 0
2865 return CR_Replace; 0
2866 ----
2867 // If the other live range is killed by DefMI and the live ranges are still ----
2868 // overlapping, it must be because we're looking at an early clobber def: ----
2869 // ----
2870 // %dst = ASM killed %src ----
2871 // ----
2872 // In this case, it is illegal to merge the two live ranges since the early ----
2873 // clobber def would clobber %src before it was read. ----
2874 if (OtherLRQ.isKill()) { 0
2875 // This case where the def doesn't overlap the kill is handled above. ----
2876 assert(VNI->def.isEarlyClobber() && 0
2877 "Only early clobber defs can overlap a kill"); ----
2878 return CR_Impossible; 0
2879 } ----
2880 ----
2881 // VNI is clobbering live lanes in OtherVNI, but there is still the ----
2882 // possibility that no instructions actually read the clobbered lanes. ----
2883 // If we're clobbering all the lanes in OtherVNI, at least one must be read. ----
2884 // Otherwise Other.RI wouldn't be live here. ----
2885 if ((TRI->getSubRegIndexLaneMask(Other.SubIdx) & ~V.WriteLanes).none()) 0
2886 return CR_Impossible; 0
2887 ----
2888 if (TrackSubRegLiveness) { 0
2889 auto &OtherLI = LIS->getInterval(Other.Reg); 0
2890 // If OtherVNI does not have subranges, it means all the lanes of OtherVNI ----
2891 // share the same live range, so we just need to check whether they have ----
2892 // any conflict bit in their LaneMask. ----
2893 if (!OtherLI.hasSubRanges()) { 0
2894 LaneBitmask OtherMask = TRI->getSubRegIndexLaneMask(Other.SubIdx); 0
2895 return (OtherMask & V.WriteLanes).none() ? CR_Replace : CR_Impossible; 0
2896 } ----
2897 ----
2898 // If we are clobbering some active lanes of OtherVNI at VNI->def, it is ----
2899 // impossible to resolve the conflict. Otherwise, we can just replace ----
2900 // OtherVNI because of no real conflict. ----
2901 for (LiveInterval::SubRange &OtherSR : OtherLI.subranges()) { 0
2902 LaneBitmask OtherMask = ----
2903 TRI->composeSubRegIndexLaneMask(Other.SubIdx, OtherSR.LaneMask); 0
2904 if ((OtherMask & V.WriteLanes).none()) 0
2905 continue; 0
2906 ----
2907 auto OtherSRQ = OtherSR.Query(VNI->def); 0
2908 if (OtherSRQ.valueIn() && OtherSRQ.endPoint() > VNI->def) { 0
2909 // VNI is clobbering some lanes of OtherVNI, they have real conflict. ----
2910 return CR_Impossible; 0
2911 } ----
2912 } ----
2913 ----
2914 // VNI is NOT clobbering any lane of OtherVNI, just replace OtherVNI. ----
2915 return CR_Replace; 0
2916 } ----
2917 ----
2918 // We need to verify that no instructions are reading the clobbered lanes. ----
2919 // To save compile time, we'll only check that locally. Don't allow the ----
2920 // tainted value to escape the basic block. ----
2921 MachineBasicBlock *MBB = Indexes->getMBBFromIndex(VNI->def); 0
2922 if (OtherLRQ.endPoint() >= Indexes->getMBBEndIdx(MBB)) 0
2923 return CR_Impossible; 0
2924 ----
2925 // There are still some things that could go wrong besides clobbered lanes ----
2926 // being read, for example OtherVNI may be only partially redefined in MBB, ----
2927 // and some clobbered lanes could escape the block. Save this analysis for ----
2928 // resolveConflicts() when all values have been mapped. We need to know ----
2929 // RedefVNI and WriteLanes for any later defs in MBB, and we can't compute ----
2930 // that now - the recursive analyzeValue() calls must go upwards in the ----
2931 // dominator tree. ----
2932 return CR_Unresolved; 0
2933 } ----
2934 ----
2935 void JoinVals::computeAssignment(unsigned ValNo, JoinVals &Other) { 0
2936 Val &V = Vals[ValNo]; 0
2937 if (V.isAnalyzed()) { 0
2938 // Recursion should always move up the dominator tree, so ValNo is not ----
2939 // supposed to reappear before it has been assigned. ----
2940 assert(Assignments[ValNo] != -1 && "Bad recursion?"); 0
2941 return; 0
2942 } ----
2943 switch ((V.Resolution = analyzeValue(ValNo, Other))) { 0
2944 case CR_Erase: 0
2945 case CR_Merge: ----
2946 // Merge this ValNo into OtherVNI. ----
2947 assert(V.OtherVNI && "OtherVNI not assigned, can't merge."); 0
2948 assert(Other.Vals[V.OtherVNI->id].isAnalyzed() && "Missing recursion"); 0
2949 Assignments[ValNo] = Other.Assignments[V.OtherVNI->id]; 0
2950 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "\t\tmerge " << printReg(Reg) << ':' << ValNo << '@' 0
2951 << LR.getValNumInfo(ValNo)->def << " into " ----
2952 << printReg(Other.Reg) << ':' << V.OtherVNI->id << '@' ----
2953 << V.OtherVNI->def << " --> @" ----
2954 << NewVNInfo[Assignments[ValNo]]->def << '\n'); ----
2955 break; 0
2956 case CR_Replace: 0
2957 case CR_Unresolved: { ----
2958 // The other value is going to be pruned if this join is successful. ----
2959 assert(V.OtherVNI && "OtherVNI not assigned, can't prune"); 0
2960 Val &OtherV = Other.Vals[V.OtherVNI->id]; 0
2961 // We cannot erase an IMPLICIT_DEF if we don't have valid values for all ----
2962 // its lanes. ----
2963 if (OtherV.ErasableImplicitDef && 0
2964 TrackSubRegLiveness && 0
2965 (OtherV.ValidLanes & ~V.ValidLanes).any()) { 0
2966 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Cannot erase implicit_def with missing values\n"); 0
2967 ----
2968 OtherV.ErasableImplicitDef = false; 0
2969 // The valid lanes written by the implicit_def were speculatively cleared ----
2970 // before, so make this more conservative. It may be better to track this, ----
2971 // I haven't found a testcase where it matters. ----
2972 OtherV.ValidLanes = LaneBitmask::getAll(); 0
2973 } ----
2974 ----
2975 OtherV.Pruned = true; 0
2976 [[fallthrough]]; ----
2977 } ----
2978 default: 0
2979 // This value number needs to go in the final joined live range. ----
2980 Assignments[ValNo] = NewVNInfo.size(); 0
2981 NewVNInfo.push_back(LR.getValNumInfo(ValNo)); 0
2982 break; 0
2983 } ----
2984 } ----
2985 ----
2986 bool JoinVals::mapValues(JoinVals &Other) { 0
2987 for (unsigned i = 0, e = LR.getNumValNums(); i != e; ++i) { 0
2988 computeAssignment(i, Other); 0
2989 if (Vals[i].Resolution == CR_Impossible) { 0
2990 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "\t\tinterference at " << printReg(Reg) << ':' << i 0
2991 << '@' << LR.getValNumInfo(i)->def << '\n'); ----
2992 return false; 0
2993 } ----
2994 } ----
2995 return true; 0
2996 } ----
2997 ----
2998 bool JoinVals:: 0
2999 taintExtent(unsigned ValNo, LaneBitmask TaintedLanes, JoinVals &Other, ----
3000 SmallVectorImpl> &TaintExtent) { ----
3001 VNInfo *VNI = LR.getValNumInfo(ValNo); 0
3002 MachineBasicBlock *MBB = Indexes->getMBBFromIndex(VNI->def); 0
3003 SlotIndex MBBEnd = Indexes->getMBBEndIdx(MBB); 0
3004 ----
3005 // Scan Other.LR from VNI.def to MBBEnd. ----
3006 LiveInterval::iterator OtherI = Other.LR.find(VNI->def); 0
3007 assert(OtherI != Other.LR.end() && "No conflict?"); 0
3008 do { ----
3009 // OtherI is pointing to a tainted value. Abort the join if the tainted ----
3010 // lanes escape the block. ----
3011 SlotIndex End = OtherI->end; 0
3012 if (End >= MBBEnd) { 0
3013 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "\t\ttaints global " << printReg(Other.Reg) << ':' 0
3014 << OtherI->valno->id << '@' << OtherI->start << '\n'); ----
3015 return false; 0
3016 } ----
3017 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "\t\ttaints local " << printReg(Other.Reg) << ':' 0
3018 << OtherI->valno->id << '@' << OtherI->start << " to " ----
3019 << End << '\n'); ----
3020 // A dead def is not a problem. ----
3021 if (End.isDead()) 0
3022 break; 0
3023 TaintExtent.push_back(std::make_pair(End, TaintedLanes)); 0
3024 ----
3025 // Check for another def in the MBB. ----
3026 if (++OtherI == Other.LR.end() || OtherI->start >= MBBEnd) 0
3027 break; 0
3028 ----
3029 // Lanes written by the new def are no longer tainted. ----
3030 const Val &OV = Other.Vals[OtherI->valno->id]; 0
3031 TaintedLanes &= ~OV.WriteLanes; 0
3032 if (!OV.RedefVNI) 0
3033 break; 0
3034 } while (TaintedLanes.any()); 0
3035 return true; 0
3036 } ----
3037 ----
3038 bool JoinVals::usesLanes(const MachineInstr &MI, Register Reg, unsigned SubIdx, 0
3039 LaneBitmask Lanes) const { ----
3040 if (MI.isDebugOrPseudoInstr()) 0
3041 return false; 0
3042 for (const MachineOperand &MO : MI.all_uses()) { 0
3043 if (MO.getReg() != Reg) 0
3044 continue; 0
3045 if (!MO.readsReg()) 0
3046 continue; 0
3047 unsigned S = TRI->composeSubRegIndices(SubIdx, MO.getSubReg()); 0
3048 if ((Lanes & TRI->getSubRegIndexLaneMask(S)).any()) 0
3049 return true; 0
3050 } ----
3051 return false; 0
3052 } ----
3053 ----
3054 bool JoinVals::resolveConflicts(JoinVals &Other) { 0
3055 for (unsigned i = 0, e = LR.getNumValNums(); i != e; ++i) { 0
3056 Val &V = Vals[i]; 0
3057 assert(V.Resolution != CR_Impossible && "Unresolvable conflict"); 0
3058 if (V.Resolution != CR_Unresolved) 0
3059 continue; 0
3060 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "\t\tconflict at " << printReg(Reg) << ':' << i << '@' 0
3061 << LR.getValNumInfo(i)->def ----
3062 << ' ' << PrintLaneMask(LaneMask) << '\n'); ----
3063 if (SubRangeJoin) 0
3064 return false; 0
3065 ----
3066 ++NumLaneConflicts; 0
3067 assert(V.OtherVNI && "Inconsistent conflict resolution."); 0
3068 VNInfo *VNI = LR.getValNumInfo(i); 0
3069 const Val &OtherV = Other.Vals[V.OtherVNI->id]; 0
3070 ----
3071 // VNI is known to clobber some lanes in OtherVNI. If we go ahead with the ----
3072 // join, those lanes will be tainted with a wrong value. Get the extent of ----
3073 // the tainted lanes. ----
3074 LaneBitmask TaintedLanes = V.WriteLanes & OtherV.ValidLanes; 0
3075 SmallVector, 8> TaintExtent; 0
3076 if (!taintExtent(i, TaintedLanes, Other, TaintExtent)) 0
3077 // Tainted lanes would extend beyond the basic block. ----
3078 return false; 0
3079 ----
3080 assert(!TaintExtent.empty() && "There should be at least one conflict."); 0
3081 ----
3082 // Now look at the instructions from VNI->def to TaintExtent (inclusive). ----
3083 MachineBasicBlock *MBB = Indexes->getMBBFromIndex(VNI->def); 0
3084 MachineBasicBlock::iterator MI = MBB->begin(); 0
3085 if (!VNI->isPHIDef()) { 0
3086 MI = Indexes->getInstructionFromIndex(VNI->def); 0
3087 if (!VNI->def.isEarlyClobber()) { 0
3088 // No need to check the instruction defining VNI for reads. ----
3089 ++MI; 0
3090 } ----
3091 } ----
3092 assert(!SlotIndex::isSameInstr(VNI->def, TaintExtent.front().first) && 0
3093 "Interference ends on VNI->def. Should have been handled earlier"); ----
3094 MachineInstr *LastMI = ----
3095 Indexes->getInstructionFromIndex(TaintExtent.front().first); 0
3096 assert(LastMI && "Range must end at a proper instruction"); 0
3097 unsigned TaintNum = 0; 0
3098 while (true) { ----
3099 assert(MI != MBB->end() && "Bad LastMI"); 0
3100 if (usesLanes(*MI, Other.Reg, Other.SubIdx, TaintedLanes)) { 0
3101 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "\t\ttainted lanes used by: " << *MI); 0
3102 return false; 0
3103 } ----
3104 // LastMI is the last instruction to use the current value. ----
3105 if (&*MI == LastMI) { 0
3106 if (++TaintNum == TaintExtent.size()) 0
3107 break; 0
3108 LastMI = Indexes->getInstructionFromIndex(TaintExtent[TaintNum].first); 0
3109 assert(LastMI && "Range must end at a proper instruction"); 0
3110 TaintedLanes = TaintExtent[TaintNum].second; 0
3111 } ----
3112 ++MI; 0
3113 } ----
3114 ----
3115 // The tainted lanes are unused. ----
3116 V.Resolution = CR_Replace; 0
3117 ++NumLaneResolves; 0
3118 } 0
3119 return true; 0
3120 } ----
3121 ----
3122 bool JoinVals::isPrunedValue(unsigned ValNo, JoinVals &Other) { 0
3123 Val &V = Vals[ValNo]; 0
3124 if (V.Pruned || V.PrunedComputed) 0
3125 return V.Pruned; 0
3126 ----
3127 if (V.Resolution != CR_Erase && V.Resolution != CR_Merge) 0
3128 return V.Pruned; 0
3129 ----
3130 // Follow copies up the dominator tree and check if any intermediate value ----
3131 // has been pruned. ----
3132 V.PrunedComputed = true; 0
3133 V.Pruned = Other.isPrunedValue(V.OtherVNI->id, *this); 0
3134 return V.Pruned; 0
3135 } ----
3136 ----
3137 void JoinVals::pruneValues(JoinVals &Other, 0
3138 SmallVectorImpl &EndPoints, ----
3139 bool changeInstrs) { ----
3140 for (unsigned i = 0, e = LR.getNumValNums(); i != e; ++i) { 0
3141 SlotIndex Def = LR.getValNumInfo(i)->def; 0
3142 switch (Vals[i].Resolution) { 0
3143 case CR_Keep: 0
3144 break; 0
3145 case CR_Replace: { 0
3146 // This value takes precedence over the value in Other.LR. ----
3147 LIS->pruneValue(Other.LR, Def, &EndPoints); 0
3148 // Check if we're replacing an IMPLICIT_DEF value. The IMPLICIT_DEF ----
3149 // instructions are only inserted to provide a live-out value for PHI ----
3150 // predecessors, so the instruction should simply go away once its value ----
3151 // has been replaced. ----
3152 Val &OtherV = Other.Vals[Vals[i].OtherVNI->id]; 0
3153 bool EraseImpDef = OtherV.ErasableImplicitDef && 0
3154 OtherV.Resolution == CR_Keep; 0
3155 if (!Def.isBlock()) { 0
3156 if (changeInstrs) { 0
3157 // Remove flags. This def is now a partial redef. ----
3158 // Also remove dead flags since the joined live range will ----
3159 // continue past this instruction. ----
3160 for (MachineOperand &MO : 0
3161 Indexes->getInstructionFromIndex(Def)->operands()) { 0
3162 if (MO.isReg() && MO.isDef() && MO.getReg() == Reg) { 0
3163 if (MO.getSubReg() != 0 && MO.isUndef() && !EraseImpDef) 0
3164 MO.setIsUndef(false); 0
3165 MO.setIsDead(false); 0
3166 } ----
3167 } ----
3168 } ----
3169 // This value will reach instructions below, but we need to make sure ----
3170 // the live range also reaches the instruction at Def. ----
3171 if (!EraseImpDef) 0
3172 EndPoints.push_back(Def); 0
3173 } ----
3174 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "\t\tpruned " << printReg(Other.Reg) << " at " << Def 0
3175 << ": " << Other.LR << '\n'); ----
3176 break; 0
3177 } ----
3178 case CR_Erase: 0
3179 case CR_Merge: ----
3180 if (isPrunedValue(i, Other)) { 0
3181 // This value is ultimately a copy of a pruned value in LR or Other.LR. ----
3182 // We can no longer trust the value mapping computed by ----
3183 // computeAssignment(), the value that was originally copied could have ----
3184 // been replaced. ----
3185 LIS->pruneValue(LR, Def, &EndPoints); 0
3186 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "\t\tpruned all of " << printReg(Reg) << " at " 0
3187 << Def << ": " << LR << '\n'); ----
3188 } ----
3189 break; 0
3190 case CR_Unresolved: 0
3191 case CR_Impossible: ----
3192 llvm_unreachable("Unresolved conflicts"); 0
3193 } ----
3194 } ----
3195 } 0
3196 ----
3197 // Check if the segment consists of a copied live-through value (i.e. the copy ----
3198 // in the block only extended the liveness, of an undef value which we may need ----
3199 // to handle). ----
3200 static bool isLiveThrough(const LiveQueryResult Q) { 0
3201 return Q.valueIn() && Q.valueIn()->isPHIDef() && Q.valueIn() == Q.valueOut(); 0
3202 } ----
3203 ----
3204 /// Consider the following situation when coalescing the copy between ----
3205 /// %31 and %45 at 800. (The vertical lines represent live range segments.) ----
3206 /// ----
3207 /// Main range Subrange 0004 (sub2) ----
3208 /// %31 %45 %31 %45 ----
3209 /// 544 %45 = COPY %28 + + ----
3210 /// | v1 | v1 ----
3211 /// 560B bb.1: + + ----
3212 /// 624 = %45.sub2 | v2 | v2 ----
3213 /// 800 %31 = COPY %45 + + + + ----
3214 /// | v0 | v0 ----
3215 /// 816 %31.sub1 = ... + | ----
3216 /// 880 %30 = COPY %31 | v1 + ----
3217 /// 928 %45 = COPY %30 | + + ----
3218 /// | | v0 | v0 <--+ ----
3219 /// 992B ; backedge -> bb.1 | + + | ----
3220 /// 1040 = %31.sub0 + | ----
3221 /// This value must remain ----
3222 /// live-out! ----
3223 /// ----
3224 /// Assuming that %31 is coalesced into %45, the copy at 928 becomes ----
3225 /// redundant, since it copies the value from %45 back into it. The ----
3226 /// conflict resolution for the main range determines that %45.v0 is ----
3227 /// to be erased, which is ok since %31.v1 is identical to it. ----
3228 /// The problem happens with the subrange for sub2: it has to be live ----
3229 /// on exit from the block, but since 928 was actually a point of ----
3230 /// definition of %45.sub2, %45.sub2 was not live immediately prior ----
3231 /// to that definition. As a result, when 928 was erased, the value v0 ----
3232 /// for %45.sub2 was pruned in pruneSubRegValues. Consequently, an ----
3233 /// IMPLICIT_DEF was inserted as a "backedge" definition for %45.sub2, ----
3234 /// providing an incorrect value to the use at 624. ----
3235 /// ----
3236 /// Since the main-range values %31.v1 and %45.v0 were proved to be ----
3237 /// identical, the corresponding values in subranges must also be the ----
3238 /// same. A redundant copy is removed because it's not needed, and not ----
3239 /// because it copied an undefined value, so any liveness that originated ----
3240 /// from that copy cannot disappear. When pruning a value that started ----
3241 /// at the removed copy, the corresponding identical value must be ----
3242 /// extended to replace it. ----
3243 void JoinVals::pruneSubRegValues(LiveInterval &LI, LaneBitmask &ShrinkMask) { 0
3244 // Look for values being erased. ----
3245 bool DidPrune = false; 0
3246 for (unsigned i = 0, e = LR.getNumValNums(); i != e; ++i) { 0
3247 Val &V = Vals[i]; 0
3248 // We should trigger in all cases in which eraseInstrs() does something. ----
3249 // match what eraseInstrs() is doing, print a message so ----
3250 if (V.Resolution != CR_Erase && 0
3251 (V.Resolution != CR_Keep || !V.ErasableImplicitDef || !V.Pruned)) 0
3252 continue; 0
3253 ----
3254 // Check subranges at the point where the copy will be removed. ----
3255 SlotIndex Def = LR.getValNumInfo(i)->def; 0
3256 SlotIndex OtherDef; 0
3257 if (V.Identical) 0
3258 OtherDef = V.OtherVNI->def; 0
3259 ----
3260 // Print message so mismatches with eraseInstrs() can be diagnosed. ----
3261 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "\t\tExpecting instruction removal at " << Def 0
3262 << '\n'); ----
3263 for (LiveInterval::SubRange &S : LI.subranges()) { 0
3264 LiveQueryResult Q = S.Query(Def); 0
3265 ----
3266 // If a subrange starts at the copy then an undefined value has been ----
3267 // copied and we must remove that subrange value as well. ----
3268 VNInfo *ValueOut = Q.valueOutOrDead(); 0
3269 if (ValueOut != nullptr && (Q.valueIn() == nullptr || 0
3270 (V.Identical && V.Resolution == CR_Erase && 0
3271 ValueOut->def == Def))) { 0
3272 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "\t\tPrune sublane " << PrintLaneMask(S.LaneMask) 0
3273 << " at " << Def << "\n"); ----
3274 SmallVector EndPoints; 0
3275 LIS->pruneValue(S, Def, &EndPoints); 0
3276 DidPrune = true; 0
3277 // Mark value number as unused. ----
3278 ValueOut->markUnused(); 0
3279 ----
3280 if (V.Identical && S.Query(OtherDef).valueOutOrDead()) { 0
3281 // If V is identical to V.OtherVNI (and S was live at OtherDef), ----
3282 // then we can't simply prune V from S. V needs to be replaced ----
3283 // with V.OtherVNI. ----
3284 LIS->extendToIndices(S, EndPoints); 0
3285 } ----
3286 ----
3287 // We may need to eliminate the subrange if the copy introduced a live ----
3288 // out undef value. ----
3289 if (ValueOut->isPHIDef()) 0
3290 ShrinkMask |= S.LaneMask; 0
3291 continue; 0
3292 } 0
3293 ----
3294 // If a subrange ends at the copy, then a value was copied but only ----
3295 // partially used later. Shrink the subregister range appropriately. ----
3296 // ----
3297 // Ultimately this calls shrinkToUses, so assuming ShrinkMask is ----
3298 // conservatively correct. ----
3299 if ((Q.valueIn() != nullptr && Q.valueOut() == nullptr) || 0
3300 (V.Resolution == CR_Erase && isLiveThrough(Q))) { 0
3301 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "\t\tDead uses at sublane " 0
3302 << PrintLaneMask(S.LaneMask) << " at " << Def ----
3303 << "\n"); ----
3304 ShrinkMask |= S.LaneMask; 0
3305 } ----
3306 } ----
3307 } ----
3308 if (DidPrune) 0
3309 LI.removeEmptySubRanges(); 0
3310 } 0
3311 ----
3312 /// Check if any of the subranges of @p LI contain a definition at @p Def. ----
3313 static bool isDefInSubRange(LiveInterval &LI, SlotIndex Def) { 0
3314 for (LiveInterval::SubRange &SR : LI.subranges()) { 0
3315 if (VNInfo *VNI = SR.Query(Def).valueOutOrDead()) 0
3316 if (VNI->def == Def) 0
3317 return true; 0
3318 } ----
3319 return false; 0
3320 } ----
3321 ----
3322 void JoinVals::pruneMainSegments(LiveInterval &LI, bool &ShrinkMainRange) { 0
3323 assert(&static_cast(LI) == &LR); 0
3324 ----
3325 for (unsigned i = 0, e = LR.getNumValNums(); i != e; ++i) { 0
3326 if (Vals[i].Resolution != CR_Keep) 0
3327 continue; 0
3328 VNInfo *VNI = LR.getValNumInfo(i); 0
3329 if (VNI->isUnused() || VNI->isPHIDef() || isDefInSubRange(LI, VNI->def)) 0
3330 continue; 0
3331 Vals[i].Pruned = true; 0
3332 ShrinkMainRange = true; 0
3333 } ----
3334 } 0
3335 ----
3336 void JoinVals::removeImplicitDefs() { 0
3337 for (unsigned i = 0, e = LR.getNumValNums(); i != e; ++i) { 0
3338 Val &V = Vals[i]; 0
3339 if (V.Resolution != CR_Keep || !V.ErasableImplicitDef || !V.Pruned) 0
3340 continue; 0
3341 ----
3342 VNInfo *VNI = LR.getValNumInfo(i); 0
3343 VNI->markUnused(); 0
3344 LR.removeValNo(VNI); 0
3345 } ----

3347 ----
3348 void JoinVals::eraseInstrs(SmallPtrSetImpl &ErasedInstrs, 0
3349 SmallVectorImpl &ShrinkRegs, ----
3350 LiveInterval *LI) { ----
3351 for (unsigned i = 0, e = LR.getNumValNums(); i != e; ++i) { 0
3352 // Get the def location before markUnused() below invalidates it. ----
3353 VNInfo *VNI = LR.getValNumInfo(i); 0
3354 SlotIndex Def = VNI->def; 0
3355 switch (Vals[i].Resolution) { 0
3356 case CR_Keep: { 0
3357 // If an IMPLICIT_DEF value is pruned, it doesn't serve a purpose any ----
3358 // longer. The IMPLICIT_DEF instructions are only inserted by ----
3359 // PHIElimination to guarantee that all PHI predecessors have a value. ----
3360 if (!Vals[i].ErasableImplicitDef || !Vals[i].Pruned) 0
3361 break; 0
3362 // Remove value number i from LR. ----
3363 // For intervals with subranges, removing a segment from the main range ----
3364 // may require extending the previous segment: for each definition of ----
3365 // a subregister, there will be a corresponding def in the main range. ----
3366 // That def may fall in the middle of a segment from another subrange. ----
3367 // In such cases, removing this def from the main range must be ----
3368 // complemented by extending the main range to account for the liveness ----
3369 // of the other subrange. ----
3370 // The new end point of the main range segment to be extended. ----
3371 SlotIndex NewEnd; 0
3372 if (LI != nullptr) { 0
3373 LiveRange::iterator I = LR.FindSegmentContaining(Def); 0
3374 assert(I != LR.end()); 0
3375 // Do not extend beyond the end of the segment being removed. ----
3376 // The segment may have been pruned in preparation for joining ----
3377 // live ranges. ----
3378 NewEnd = I->end; 0
3379 } ----
3380 ----
3381 LR.removeValNo(VNI); 0
3382 // Note that this VNInfo is reused and still referenced in NewVNInfo, ----
3383 // make it appear like an unused value number. ----
3384 VNI->markUnused(); 0
3385 ----
3386 if (LI != nullptr && LI->hasSubRanges()) { 0
3387 assert(static_cast(LI) == &LR); 0
3388 // Determine the end point based on the subrange information: ----
3389 // minimum of (earliest def of next segment, ----
3390 // latest end point of containing segment) ----
3391 SlotIndex ED, LE; 0
3392 for (LiveInterval::SubRange &SR : LI->subranges()) { 0
3393 LiveRange::iterator I = SR.find(Def); 0
3394 if (I == SR.end()) 0
3395 continue; 0
3396 if (I->start > Def) 0
3397 ED = ED.isValid() ? std::min(ED, I->start) : I->start; 0
3398 else ----
3399 LE = LE.isValid() ? std::max(LE, I->end) : I->end; 0
3400 } ----
3401 if (LE.isValid()) 0
3402 NewEnd = std::min(NewEnd, LE); 0
3403 if (ED.isValid()) 0
3404 NewEnd = std::min(NewEnd, ED); 0
3405 ----
3406 // We only want to do the extension if there was a subrange that ----
3407 // was live across Def. ----
3408 if (LE.isValid()) { 0
3409 LiveRange::iterator S = LR.find(Def); 0
3410 if (S != LR.begin()) 0
3411 std::prev(S)->end = NewEnd; 0
3412 } ----
3413 } ----
3414 LLVM_DEBUG({ 0
3415 dbgs() << "\t\tremoved " << i << '@' << Def << ": " << LR << '\n'; ----
3416 if (LI != nullptr) ----
3417 dbgs() << "\t\t LHS = " << *LI << '\n'; ----
3418 }); ----
3419 [[fallthrough]]; ----
3420 } ----
3421 ----
3422 case CR_Erase: { ----
3423 MachineInstr *MI = Indexes->getInstructionFromIndex(Def); 0
3424 assert(MI && "No instruction to erase"); 0
3425 if (MI->isCopy()) { 0
3426 Register Reg = MI->getOperand(1).getReg(); 0
3427 if (Reg.isVirtual() && Reg != CP.getSrcReg() && Reg != CP.getDstReg()) 0
3428 ShrinkRegs.push_back(Reg); 0
3429 } ----
3430 ErasedInstrs.insert(MI); 0
3431 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "\t\terased:\t" << Def << '\t' << *MI); 0
3432 LIS->RemoveMachineInstrFromMaps(*MI); 0
3433 MI->eraseFromParent(); 0
3434 break; 0
3435 } ----
3436 default: 0
3437 break; 0
3438 } ----
3439 } ----
3440 } 0
3441 ----
3442 void RegisterCoalescer::joinSubRegRanges(LiveRange &LRange, LiveRange &RRange, 0
3443 LaneBitmask LaneMask, ----
3444 const CoalescerPair &CP) { ----
3445 SmallVector NewVNInfo; 0
3446 JoinVals RHSVals(RRange, CP.getSrcReg(), CP.getSrcIdx(), LaneMask, ----
3447 NewVNInfo, CP, LIS, TRI, true, true); 0
3448 JoinVals LHSVals(LRange, CP.getDstReg(), CP.getDstIdx(), LaneMask, ----
3449 NewVNInfo, CP, LIS, TRI, true, true); 0
3450 ----
3451 // Compute NewVNInfo and resolve conflicts (see also joinVirtRegs()) ----
3452 // We should be able to resolve all conflicts here as we could successfully do ----
3453 // it on the mainrange already. There is however a problem when multiple ----
3454 // ranges get mapped to the "overflow" lane mask bit which creates unexpected ----
3455 // interferences. ----
3456 if (!LHSVals.mapValues(RHSVals) || !RHSVals.mapValues(LHSVals)) { 0
3457 // We already determined that it is legal to merge the intervals, so this ----
3458 // should never fail. ----
3459 llvm_unreachable("*** Couldn't join subrange!\n"); 0
3460 } ----
3461 if (!LHSVals.resolveConflicts(RHSVals) || 0
3462 !RHSVals.resolveConflicts(LHSVals)) { 0
3463 // We already determined that it is legal to merge the intervals, so this ----
3464 // should never fail. ----
3465 llvm_unreachable("*** Couldn't join subrange!\n"); 0
3466 } ----
3467 ----
3468 // The merging algorithm in LiveInterval::join() can't handle conflicting ----
3469 // value mappings, so we need to remove any live ranges that overlap a ----
3470 // CR_Replace resolution. Collect a set of end points that can be used to ----
3471 // restore the live range after joining. ----
3472 SmallVector EndPoints; 0
3473 LHSVals.pruneValues(RHSVals, EndPoints, false); 0
3474 RHSVals.pruneValues(LHSVals, EndPoints, false); 0
3475 ----
3476 LHSVals.removeImplicitDefs(); 0
3477 RHSVals.removeImplicitDefs(); 0
3478 ----
3479 LRange.verify(); 0
3480 RRange.verify(); 0
3481 ----
3482 // Join RRange into LHS. ----
3483 LRange.join(RRange, LHSVals.getAssignments(), RHSVals.getAssignments(), 0
3484 NewVNInfo); ----
3485 ----
3486 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "\t\tjoined lanes: " << PrintLaneMask(LaneMask) 0
3487 << ' ' << LRange << "\n"); ----
3488 if (EndPoints.empty()) 0
3489 return; 0
3490 ----
3491 // Recompute the parts of the live range we had to remove because of ----
3492 // CR_Replace conflicts. ----
3493 LLVM_DEBUG({ 0
3494 dbgs() << "\t\trestoring liveness to " << EndPoints.size() << " points: "; ----
3495 for (unsigned i = 0, n = EndPoints.size(); i != n; ++i) { ----
3496 dbgs() << EndPoints[i]; ----
3497 if (i != n-1) ----
3498 dbgs() << ','; ----
3499 } ----
3500 dbgs() << ": " << LRange << '\n'; ----
3501 }); ----
3502 LIS->extendToIndices(LRange, EndPoints); 0
3503 } 0

3505 void RegisterCoalescer::mergeSubRangeInto(LiveInterval &LI, 0

3507 LaneBitmask LaneMask, ----
3508 CoalescerPair &CP, ----
3509 unsigned ComposeSubRegIdx) { ----
3510 BumpPtrAllocator &Allocator = LIS->getVNInfoAllocator(); 0
3511 LI.refineSubRanges( 0
3512 Allocator, LaneMask, ----
3513 [this, &Allocator, &ToMerge, &CP](LiveInterval::SubRange &SR) { 0
3514 if (SR.empty()) { 0
3515 SR.assign(ToMerge, Allocator); 0
3516 } else { ----
3517 // joinSubRegRange() destroys the merged range, so we need a copy. ----
3518 LiveRange RangeCopy(ToMerge, Allocator); 0
3519 joinSubRegRanges(SR, RangeCopy, SR.LaneMask, CP); 0
3520 } 0
3521 }, 0
3522 *LIS->getSlotIndexes(), *TRI, ComposeSubRegIdx); 0

3526 if (LI.valnos.size() < LargeIntervalSizeThreshold) 0
3527 return false; 0
3528 auto &Counter = LargeLIVisitCounter[LI.reg()]; 0
3529 if (Counter < LargeIntervalFreqThreshold) { 0
3530 Counter++; 0
3531 return false; 0
3532 } ----
3533 return true; 0

3535 ----
3536 bool RegisterCoalescer::joinVirtRegs(CoalescerPair &CP) { 0
3537 SmallVector NewVNInfo; 0
3538 LiveInterval &RHS = LIS->getInterval(CP.getSrcReg()); 0
3539 LiveInterval &LHS = LIS->getInterval(CP.getDstReg()); 0
3540 bool TrackSubRegLiveness = MRI->shouldTrackSubRegLiveness(*CP.getNewRC()); 0
3541 JoinVals RHSVals(RHS, CP.getSrcReg(), CP.getSrcIdx(), LaneBitmask::getNone(), ----
3542 NewVNInfo, CP, LIS, TRI, false, TrackSubRegLiveness); 0
3543 JoinVals LHSVals(LHS, CP.getDstReg(), CP.getDstIdx(), LaneBitmask::getNone(), ----
3544 NewVNInfo, CP, LIS, TRI, false, TrackSubRegLiveness); 0
3545 ----
3546 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "\t\tRHS = " << RHS << "\n\t\tLHS = " << LHS << '\n'); 0
3547 ----
3548 if (isHighCostLiveInterval(LHS) || isHighCostLiveInterval(RHS)) 0
3549 return false; 0
3550 ----
3551 // First compute NewVNInfo and the simple value mappings. ----
3552 // Detect impossible conflicts early. ----
3553 if (!LHSVals.mapValues(RHSVals) || !RHSVals.mapValues(LHSVals)) 0
3554 return false; 0
3555 ----
3556 // Some conflicts can only be resolved after all values have been mapped. ----
3557 if (!LHSVals.resolveConflicts(RHSVals) || !RHSVals.resolveConflicts(LHSVals)) 0
3558 return false; 0
3559 ----
3560 // All clear, the live ranges can be merged. ----
3561 if (RHS.hasSubRanges() || LHS.hasSubRanges()) { 0
3562 BumpPtrAllocator &Allocator = LIS->getVNInfoAllocator(); 0
3563 ----
3564 // Transform lanemasks from the LHS to masks in the coalesced register and ----
3565 // create initial subranges if necessary. ----
3566 unsigned DstIdx = CP.getDstIdx(); 0
3567 if (!LHS.hasSubRanges()) { 0
3568 LaneBitmask Mask = DstIdx == 0 ? CP.getNewRC()->getLaneMask() 0
3569 : TRI->getSubRegIndexLaneMask(DstIdx); 0
3570 // LHS must support subregs or we wouldn't be in this codepath. ----
3571 assert(Mask.any()); 0
3572 LHS.createSubRangeFrom(Allocator, Mask, LHS); 0
3573 } else if (DstIdx != 0) { 0
3574 // Transform LHS lanemasks to new register class if necessary. ----
3575 for (LiveInterval::SubRange &R : LHS.subranges()) { 0
3576 LaneBitmask Mask = TRI->composeSubRegIndexLaneMask(DstIdx, R.LaneMask); 0
3577 R.LaneMask = Mask; 0
3578 } ----
3579 } ----
3580 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "\t\tLHST = " << printReg(CP.getDstReg()) << ' ' << LHS 0
3581 << '\n'); ----
3582 ----
3583 // Determine lanemasks of RHS in the coalesced register and merge subranges. ----
3584 unsigned SrcIdx = CP.getSrcIdx(); 0
3585 if (!RHS.hasSubRanges()) { 0
3586 LaneBitmask Mask = SrcIdx == 0 ? CP.getNewRC()->getLaneMask() 0
3587 : TRI->getSubRegIndexLaneMask(SrcIdx); 0
3588 mergeSubRangeInto(LHS, RHS, Mask, CP, DstIdx); 0
3589 } else { ----
3590 // Pair up subranges and merge. ----
3591 for (LiveInterval::SubRange &R : RHS.subranges()) { 0
3592 LaneBitmask Mask = TRI->composeSubRegIndexLaneMask(SrcIdx, R.LaneMask); 0
3593 mergeSubRangeInto(LHS, R, Mask, CP, DstIdx); 0
3594 } ----
3595 } ----
3596 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "\tJoined SubRanges " << LHS << "\n"); 0
3597 ----
3598 // Pruning implicit defs from subranges may result in the main range ----
3599 // having stale segments. ----
3600 LHSVals.pruneMainSegments(LHS, ShrinkMainRange); 0
3601 ----
3602 LHSVals.pruneSubRegValues(LHS, ShrinkMask); 0
3603 RHSVals.pruneSubRegValues(LHS, ShrinkMask); 0
3604 } ----
3605 ----
3606 // The merging algorithm in LiveInterval::join() can't handle conflicting ----
3607 // value mappings, so we need to remove any live ranges that overlap a ----
3608 // CR_Replace resolution. Collect a set of end points that can be used to ----
3609 // restore the live range after joining. ----
3610 SmallVector EndPoints; 0
3611 LHSVals.pruneValues(RHSVals, EndPoints, true); 0
3612 RHSVals.pruneValues(LHSVals, EndPoints, true); 0
3613 ----
3614 // Erase COPY and IMPLICIT_DEF instructions. This may cause some external ----
3615 // registers to require trimming. ----
3616 SmallVector ShrinkRegs; 0
3617 LHSVals.eraseInstrs(ErasedInstrs, ShrinkRegs, &LHS); 0
3618 RHSVals.eraseInstrs(ErasedInstrs, ShrinkRegs); 0
3619 while (!ShrinkRegs.empty()) 0
3620 shrinkToUses(&LIS->getInterval(ShrinkRegs.pop_back_val())); 0
3621 ----
3622 // Scan and mark undef any DBG_VALUEs that would refer to a different value. ----
3623 checkMergingChangesDbgValues(CP, LHS, LHSVals, RHS, RHSVals); 0
3624 ----
3625 // If the RHS covers any PHI locations that were tracked for debug-info, we ----
3626 // must update tracking information to reflect the join. ----
3627 auto RegIt = RegToPHIIdx.find(CP.getSrcReg()); 0
3628 if (RegIt != RegToPHIIdx.end()) { 0
3629 // Iterate over all the debug instruction numbers assigned this register. ----
3630 for (unsigned InstID : RegIt->second) { 0
3631 auto PHIIt = PHIValToPos.find(InstID); 0
3632 assert(PHIIt != PHIValToPos.end()); 0
3633 const SlotIndex &SI = PHIIt->second.SI; 0
3634 ----
3635 // Does the RHS cover the position of this PHI? ----
3636 auto LII = RHS.find(SI); 0
3637 if (LII == RHS.end() || LII->start > SI) 0
3638 continue; 0
3639 ----
3640 // Accept two kinds of subregister movement: ----
3641 // * When we merge from one register class into a larger register: ----
3642 // %1:gr16 = some-inst ----
3643 // -> ----
3644 // %2:gr32.sub_16bit = some-inst ----
3645 // * When the PHI is already in a subregister, and the larger class ----
3646 // is coalesced: ----
3647 // %2:gr32.sub_16bit = some-inst ----
3648 // %3:gr32 = COPY %2 ----
3649 // -> ----
3650 // %3:gr32.sub_16bit = some-inst ----
3651 // Test for subregister move: ----

3656 continue; 0

3678 InstrNums.end()); ----

3776 ----
3777 void RegisterCoalescer::checkMergingChangesDbgValuesImpl(Register Reg, 0
3778 LiveRange &OtherLR, ----
3779 LiveRange &RegLR, ----
3780 JoinVals &RegVals) { ----
3781 // Are there any DBG_VALUEs to examine? ----
3782 auto VRegMapIt = DbgVRegToValues.find(Reg); 0
3783 if (VRegMapIt == DbgVRegToValues.end()) 0
3784 return; 0
3785 ----
3786 auto &DbgValueSet = VRegMapIt->second; 0
3787 auto DbgValueSetIt = DbgValueSet.begin(); 0
3788 auto SegmentIt = OtherLR.begin(); 0
3789 ----
3790 bool LastUndefResult = false; 0
3791 SlotIndex LastUndefIdx; 0
3792 ----
3793 // If the "Other" register is live at a slot Idx, test whether Reg can ----
3794 // safely be merged with it, or should be marked undef. ----
3795 auto ShouldUndef = [&RegVals, &RegLR, &LastUndefResult, 0
3796 &LastUndefIdx](SlotIndex Idx) -> bool { 0
3797 // Our worst-case performance typically happens with asan, causing very ----
3798 // many DBG_VALUEs of the same location. Cache a copy of the most recent ----
3799 // result for this edge-case. ----
3800 if (LastUndefIdx == Idx) 0
3801 return LastUndefResult; 0
3802 ----
3803 // If the other range was live, and Reg's was not, the register coalescer ----
3804 // will not have tried to resolve any conflicts. We don't know whether ----
3805 // the DBG_VALUE will refer to the same value number, so it must be made ----
3806 // undef. ----
3807 auto OtherIt = RegLR.find(Idx); 0
3808 if (OtherIt == RegLR.end()) 0
3809 return true; 0
3810 ----
3811 // Both the registers were live: examine the conflict resolution record for ----
3812 // the value number Reg refers to. CR_Keep meant that this value number ----
3813 // "won" and the merged register definitely refers to that value. CR_Erase ----
3814 // means the value number was a redundant copy of the other value, which ----
3815 // was coalesced and Reg deleted. It's safe to refer to the other register ----
3816 // (which will be the source of the copy). ----
3817 auto Resolution = RegVals.getResolution(OtherIt->valno->id); 0
3818 LastUndefResult = Resolution != JoinVals::CR_Keep && 0
3819 Resolution != JoinVals::CR_Erase; ----
3820 LastUndefIdx = Idx; 0
3821 return LastUndefResult; 0
3822 }; 0
3823 ----
3824 // Iterate over both the live-range of the "Other" register, and the set of ----
3825 // DBG_VALUEs for Reg at the same time. Advance whichever one has the lowest ----
3826 // slot index. This relies on the DbgValueSet being ordered. ----
3827 while (DbgValueSetIt != DbgValueSet.end() && SegmentIt != OtherLR.end()) { 0
3828 if (DbgValueSetIt->first < SegmentIt->end) { 0
3829 // "Other" is live and there is a DBG_VALUE of Reg: test if we should ----
3830 // set it undef. ----
3831 if (DbgValueSetIt->first >= SegmentIt->start) { 0
3832 bool HasReg = DbgValueSetIt->second->hasDebugOperandForReg(Reg); 0
3833 bool ShouldUndefReg = ShouldUndef(DbgValueSetIt->first); 0
3834 if (HasReg && ShouldUndefReg) { 0
3835 // Mark undef, erase record of this DBG_VALUE to avoid revisiting. ----
3836 DbgValueSetIt->second->setDebugValueUndef(); 0
3837 continue; 0
3838 } ----
3839 } ----
3840 ++DbgValueSetIt; 0
3841 } else { ----
3842 ++SegmentIt; 0
3843 } ----
3844 } ----
3845 } ----

3861 /// C-style comparator that sorts first based on the loop depth of the basic ----
3862 /// block (the unsigned), and then on the MBB number. ----
3863 /// ----
3864 /// EnableGlobalCopies assumes that the primary sort key is loop depth. ----
3865 static int compareMBBPriority(const MBBPriorityInfo *LHS, 8 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
3866 const MBBPriorityInfo *RHS) { ----
3867 // Deeper loops first ----
3868 if (LHS->Depth != RHS->Depth) 8 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
3869 return LHS->Depth > RHS->Depth ? -1 : 1; 0
3870 ----
3871 // Try to unsplit critical edges next. ----
3872 if (LHS->IsSplit != RHS->IsSplit) 8 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
3873 return LHS->IsSplit ? -1 : 1; 0
3874 ----
3875 // Prefer blocks that are more connected in the CFG. This takes care of ----
3876 // the most difficult copies first while intervals are short. ----
3877 unsigned cl = LHS->MBB->pred_size() + LHS->MBB->succ_size(); 8 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
3878 unsigned cr = RHS->MBB->pred_size() + RHS->MBB->succ_size(); 8 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
3879 if (cl != cr) 8 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
3880 return cl > cr ? -1 : 1; 0
3881 ----
3882 // As a last resort, sort by block number. ----
3883 return LHS->MBB->getNumber() < RHS->MBB->getNumber() ? -1 : 1; 8 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
3884 } ----
